---
import PageLayout from "@/layouts/Base.astro";
---

<PageLayout
	meta={{
		title: "Venue and Location",
		description:
			"Venue, travel, and accommodation information for the 1st German-Japanese Summer School on Human-Centred Perception Modelling in XR, NAIST, Nara, Japan.",
	}}
>
	<!-- ── PAGE BANNER ───────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
	<!--
		Banner image: NAIST facilities (official NAIST photo).
		Replace with own photo: upload to /public/images/venue-banner.jpg
	-->
	<section class="-mx-4 sm:-mx-8 -mt-4 relative mb-12 overflow-hidden">
		<img
			src="https://www.naist.jp/mt-static/support/theme_static/naist_en_main/images/facilities/facilities_cover2.jpg"
			alt="NAIST campus, Ikoma, Nara"
			width="1280"
			height="220"
			class="w-full object-cover"
			style="height: 220px; object-position: center 50%;"
		/>
		<div
			class="absolute inset-0 flex items-end"
			style="background: linear-gradient(to top, rgba(0,0,0,0.75) 0%, rgba(0,0,0,0.0) 70%);"
		>
			<div class="w-full p-5 sm:p-8">
				<h1 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white">Venue and Location</h1>
				<p class="mt-1 text-sm text-white/70">NAIST, Ikoma, Nara Prefecture, Japan</p>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>

	<!-- ── THE VENUE ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
	<section class="mb-14">
		<h2 class="title mb-4 text-xl">The Venue</h2>

		<div class="mb-5 grid gap-3 sm:grid-cols-2">
			<figure>
				<div class="overflow-hidden rounded-lg">
					<img
						src="https://www.naist.jp/en/toppage-banner/img/main_entrance.png"
						alt="NAIST main entrance, Ikoma, Nara"
						width="800"
						height="200"
						class="w-full object-cover"
						style="height: 200px; object-position: center 60%;"
					/>
				</div>
				<figcaption class="text-muted mt-1.5 text-xs">NAIST main entrance</figcaption>
			</figure>
			<figure>
				<div class="overflow-hidden rounded-lg">
					<!--
						Replace with an interior or campus photo:
						upload to /public/images/naist-campus.jpg → src="/images/naist-campus.jpg"
					-->
					<img
						src="https://www.naist.jp/mt-static/support/theme_static/naist_en_main/images/facilities/facilities_cover2.jpg"
						alt="NAIST campus facilities"
						width="800"
						height="200"
						class="w-full object-cover"
						style="height: 200px; object-position: center 50%;"
					/>
				</div>
				<figcaption class="text-muted mt-1.5 text-xs">NAIST campus facilities</figcaption>
			</figure>
		</div>

		<p class="text-muted mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed">
			The summer school is hosted at the <strong class="text-global-text">Nara Institute of Science
			and Technology (NAIST)</strong>, one of Japan's leading graduate-only research universities,
			situated in Ikoma, Nara Prefecture. Founded in 1991, NAIST is known for its small, focused
			research community and strong international collaborations, particularly in information science,
			biological sciences, and materials science.
		</p>
		<p class="text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
			Address: 8916-5 Takayama-cho, Ikoma, Nara 630-0192, Japan. Website:
			<a class="cactus-link" href="https://www.naist.jp/en/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener"
				>naist.jp</a
			>
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- ── ROOMS AND FACILITIES ──────────────────────────────────────────── -->
	<section class="mb-14">
		<h2 class="title mb-4 text-xl">Rooms and Facilities</h2>

		<h3 class="text-accent-2 mb-1 font-semibold">Lecture Hall</h3>
		<p class="text-muted mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed">
			Lectures will be held in a dedicated lecture hall on the NAIST campus with modern
			audiovisual equipment including projector, screen, microphones, and recording facilities.
			The specific room will be confirmed and communicated to registered participants before the event.
		</p>

		<h3 class="text-accent-2 mb-1 font-semibold">Workshop Rooms</h3>
		<p class="text-muted mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed">
			Workshop and group work sessions will take place in seminar rooms and laboratory spaces
			equipped for collaborative work. Participants will have access to workstations, whiteboards,
			and XR hardware for prototyping sessions on Days 2 and 3.
		</p>

		<h3 class="text-accent-2 mb-1 font-semibold">Internet Access</h3>
		<p class="text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
			Eduroam is available throughout the NAIST campus. Guest Wi-Fi credentials will be provided
			to participants who do not have access to Eduroam.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- ── GETTING THERE ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
	<section class="mb-14">
		<h2 class="title mb-4 text-xl">Getting There</h2>

		<h3 class="text-accent-2 mb-1 font-semibold">Nearest Train Station</h3>
		<p class="text-muted mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed">
			The closest station is <strong class="text-global-text">Gakken-Nara-Tomigaoka</strong> on
			the Kintetsu Keihanna Line. A campus shuttle bus operates between the station and NAIST during
			event days (schedule to be confirmed). The campus is also reachable by taxi from the station
			in approximately 10 minutes.
		</p>

		<h3 class="text-accent-2 mb-1 font-semibold">From Osaka</h3>
		<p class="text-muted mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed">
			Take the Osaka Metro Chuo Line from Honmachi or Cosmosquare to Gakken-Nara-Tomigaoka
			(approximately 45 minutes). Alternatively, take the Kintetsu Osaka Line from Osaka Namba to
			Yamato-Saidaiji, then transfer to the Kintetsu Keihanna Line.
		</p>

		<h3 class="text-accent-2 mb-1 font-semibold">From Kyoto</h3>
		<p class="text-muted mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed">
			Take the Kintetsu Kyoto Line from Kintetsu-Kyoto Station (adjacent to JR Kyoto Station)
			to Yamato-Saidaiji, then transfer to the Kintetsu Keihanna Line to Gakken-Nara-Tomigaoka
			(approximately 60 minutes total).
		</p>

		<h3 class="text-accent-2 mb-1 font-semibold">From Nara City Centre</h3>
		<p class="text-muted mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed">
			Take the Kintetsu Nara Line from Kintetsu-Nara Station to Yamato-Saidaiji, then transfer to
			the Kintetsu Keihanna Line (approximately 30 minutes total).
		</p>

		<h3 class="text-accent-2 mb-1 font-semibold">From Kansai International Airport (KIX)</h3>
		<p class="text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
			Take the Nankai Airport Express (Rapi:t) to Namba, then transfer to the Osaka Metro Chuo Line
			towards Gakken-Nara-Tomigaoka (approximately 75–90 minutes total). A limousine bus service
			between KIX and Nara city is also available.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- ── ACCOMMODATION ─────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
	<section class="mb-14">
		<h2 class="title mb-4 text-xl">Accommodation</h2>

		<p class="text-muted mb-6 text-sm leading-relaxed">
			There is no on-campus accommodation at NAIST. Participants are recommended to stay in Osaka or
			Nara city centre, both of which offer excellent transport links to the campus and a wide range
			of hotels at various price points. A list of recommended hotels will be provided to registered
			participants.
		</p>

		<h3 class="text-accent-2 mb-1 font-semibold">Osaka (recommended)</h3>
		<p class="text-muted mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed">
			Staying in central Osaka (Namba, Shinsaibashi, or Umeda) offers the best combination of
			transport access, dining, and accommodation choice. The Namba and Honmachi areas are on the
			direct Osaka Metro Chuo Line to NAIST. Journey time to campus is approximately 45 minutes.
		</p>

		<h3 class="text-accent-2 mb-1 font-semibold">Nara City Centre</h3>
		<p class="text-muted mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed">
			Staying in Nara provides easy access to Nara Park and the UNESCO World Heritage sites, and is
			approximately 30 minutes to campus by Kintetsu train. Nara has a smaller hotel selection than
			Osaka but offers a quieter, more traditional atmosphere.
		</p>

		<h3 class="text-accent-2 mb-1 font-semibold">Budget Options</h3>
		<p class="text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
			Several hostels and guesthouses are available in Osaka and Nara. Japan's business hotel chains
			(Toyoko Inn, Dormy Inn, APA Hotel) offer clean, affordable rooms in both cities and are a
			popular choice for academic visitors. [Specific hotel recommendations to be added.]
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- ── PRACTICAL INFORMATION ─────────────────────────────────────────── -->
	<section class="mb-14">
		<h2 class="title mb-4 text-xl">Practical Information</h2>

		<h3 class="text-accent-2 mb-1 font-semibold">Weather in September</h3>
		<p class="text-muted mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed">
			September in the Nara/Osaka region is warm to hot, with daytime temperatures typically
			between 25 and 32 °C. Humidity begins to decrease compared to August. Light clothing is
			recommended; a light layer may be useful for air-conditioned rooms.
		</p>

		<h3 class="text-accent-2 mb-1 font-semibold">Time Zone</h3>
		<p class="text-muted mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed">
			Japan Standard Time (JST), UTC+9. Japan does not observe daylight saving time.
		</p>

		<h3 class="text-accent-2 mb-1 font-semibold">Currency</h3>
		<p class="text-muted mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed">
			Japanese Yen (JPY). Japan remains largely cash-based in many settings, though credit cards
			are accepted at larger hotels, department stores, and convenience stores. ATMs in 7-Eleven
			and Japan Post offices reliably accept international cards.
		</p>

		<h3 class="text-accent-2 mb-1 font-semibold">Visa</h3>
		<p class="text-muted mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed">
			Citizens of Germany and many other countries can enter Japan visa-free for up to 90 days for
			short-term stays. Please check the current entry requirements for your nationality before
			travelling. [Official visa information to be linked.]
		</p>

		<h3 class="text-accent-2 mb-1 font-semibold">Language</h3>
		<p class="text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
			The summer school is conducted entirely in English. Japanese is the local language; while
			English signage is common in tourist areas and at NAIST, basic knowledge of Japanese phrases
			can be helpful when travelling in Nara or Ikoma.
		</p>
	</section>

	<!-- ── LOCAL AREA ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
	<section class="mb-6">
		<h2 class="title mb-4 text-xl">Local Area</h2>
		<p class="text-muted mb-4 text-sm leading-relaxed">
			NAIST is located in Ikoma, a city on the western edge of Nara Prefecture, bordering Osaka.
			The wider Kansai region offers some of Japan's most significant cultural and historical sites
			within easy reach.
		</p>
		<p class="text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
			Nara city (30 min) is home to Todai-ji Temple, Kasuga Taisha Shrine, and the famous Nara
			Park with freely roaming deer — all UNESCO World Heritage sites. Osaka (45 min) is a major
			city known for its food culture, nightlife, and the Dotonbori entertainment district. Kyoto
			(60 min) offers an extraordinary density of temples, shrines, and traditional districts such
			as Gion and Arashiyama. The Day 4 excursion will take participants to one of these or nearby
			destinations — see the <a class="cactus-link" href="/programme/">Programme</a> for details.
		</p>
	</section>
</PageLayout>
